"The Sea Belongs to Us": a landless Bolivia hopes that the court will reopen the road to the Pacific
Sailors watch a naval headquarters in La Paz.
In public buildings waves marine blue flags.
From Lake Titicaca to the Amazon, the naval bases show the motto: "The sea belongs to us by right,
Recovering it is a duty."
Throughout Bolivia, a land without sea, they still vividly remember the coastline lost to Chile in a bloody conflict over the resources that took place in the 19th century, in addition to the longing for a return to the Pacific Ocean.
These hopes may be the biggest in decades, as Bolivia expects a resolution from the International Court of Justice for one October, after five years of discussion.
"Bolivia has the momentum, a spirit of unity and serenity and, of course, is waiting for the result with a positive vision," said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will observe the judgement of the International Court of Justice on large screens distributed throughout the country, in the hope that the Hague Court will speak in favour of Bolivia's claim that, after decades of intermittent talks, Chile has an obligation to negotiate to grant Bolivia a sovereign exit to the sea.
Evo Morales, Bolivia's charismatic indigenous president, who is waging a controversial battle for re-election next year, also has much to say about Monday's resolution.
"We are very close to returning to the Pacific Ocean," he promised at the end of August.
However, some analysts believe that it is unlikely that the court will decide for Bolivia and that the situation would change little if it did.
The United Nations body based in the Netherlands has no power to award Chilean territory and has stipulated that it will not determine the outcome of possible talks.
The fact that the International Court of Justice resolution arrives only six months after the final allegations indicates that the case "was not complicated," said Paz Zárate, Chilean expert in international law.
Far from promoting the Bolivian cause, it may have been impeded for the past four years.
"The problem of access to the sea has been kidnapped by the current Bolivian administration," Zárate said.
He also suggested that Morales' belligerent rhetoric has undermined any residual Chilean good will.
Bolivia and Chile will continue to talk at some point, but it will be extremely difficult to keep conversations after this.
The two countries have not exchanged ambassadors since 1962.
President Eduardo Rodríguez Veltzé, representative of Bolivia in The Hague, rejected the idea that the decision-making of the court was unusually rapid.
On Monday, Bolivia will be offered "an extraordinary opportunity to open a new era of relations with Chile" and the possibility of "putting an end to 139 years of disagreement with mutual benefits," he said.
Calzadilla also denied that Morales, who is still one of the most popular presidents of Latin America, would use the maritime issue as a political crutch.
"Bolivia will never renounce her right to access the Pacific Ocean," he added.
"The resolution is an opportunity to see that we have to leave behind the past."
