John Edward: Language skills are fundamental to the citizens of the world
The independent educational centres in Scotland have a career of academic excellence that has continued in 2018 with another set of extraordinary results in the examinations that are reinforced by individual and collective successes gathered in the fields of sport, art, music and other community projects.
With more than 30,000 students throughout Scotland, these centres, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Colleges (CIS) are striving to deliver the best level of service to students and parents.
The aim of the independent schools is to prepare their students to continue their higher education studies, for the career they choose and for the place they occupy as the citizens of the world.
As an educational sector that can design and implement an adapted curriculum, it is observed that modern languages remain a popular and desired subject in the centres.
As Nelson Mandela said: "If you speak a man in a language you understand, the message comes to his head.
If you speak to her in her tongue, she reaches her heart."
This is a powerful reminder that, if one wants to establish relationships and build trust with people from other countries, one cannot depend solely on English.
If we take into account the recent results of this year's exams, we can see that languages are at the top of the classification tables, being the highest approved rates in the independent schools.
A total of 68% of students studying foreign languages obtained an A, the highest grade.
Data, collected from the 74 SCIS centres, showed that 72% of students obtained an A in Mandarin, while 72% of those studying German, 69% of those studying French, and 63% of those studying Spanish also obtained an A.
This shows that the independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages because they consider them a fundamental competence that both children and young people will definitely need in the future.
At present, as a subject, languages are considered to be at the same level as the CTIM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the curricula of independent schools and everywhere.
A survey carried out in 2014 by the UK Employment and Competition Commission revealed that 17 % were attributed to the shortage of language skills for entrepreneurs in terms of the difficulties they faced in filling jobs.
Language skills are therefore increasingly needed to prepare young people for their future careers.
Possible job opportunities requiring languages are increasing, so these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the career that someone chooses, if he has learned a second language, he will have a real advantage in the future thanks to a competition like this, which will last his whole life.
Being able to communicate directly with people from foreign countries will allow that person to automatically advance to competition.
According to a survey conducted by YouGov among more than 4000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75% of them did not speak any foreign language well enough to hold a conversation. Furthermore, it was established that the only language spoken by a percentage of two digits, 15%, was French.
For this reason, investing in language education is now important for children today.
If you know several languages, especially those in developing economies, children will be equipped to have better opportunities to find quality employment.
In Scotland, each school will teach different languages.
Some centres will focus on the most classic modern languages, while others will teach languages considered most important for the United Kingdom by 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever the interests of a child, independent schools can always choose from a number of languages provided by specialized teaching staff in this field.
Scotland's independent educational centres devote all their efforts to providing a learning environment that prepares children and teams with the skills they need to succeed, whatever happens to them in the future.
At present, it is undeniable that, in a global business environment, languages continue to be of vital importance to the future of the country, so this should be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages should be considered as "competences for international communication".
Independent schools will continue to offer these options, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
We have to do this.
John Edward is the director of the Scottish Council of Independent Colleges
