North Korea says that "there is no possibility" that they will first be unilaterally disarmed if they do not have confidence
On Saturday, the Foreign Minister of North Korea informed the United Nations that the continuation of the sanctions deepened its confidence in the United States and that there was no possibility that his country would unilaterally renounce nuclear weapons under those circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho declared to the Annual General Assembly of the international agency that North Korea had taken "significant measures of goodwill" over the past year, such as quitting nuclear and missile testing, dismantling nuclear testing facilities and committing itself to non-proliferation of nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
"However, we do not receive any similar response from the United States," he said.
"If we do not have confidence in the United States, we cannot have confidence in our national security, and in these circumstances there is no possibility that we will first be unilaterally disarmed."
Although Ri reiterated the well-known North Korea complaints about Washington's resistance to a phase-out denuclearization formula that rewards the country as it takes gradual steps, his statement is important, as he did not reject a unilateral denuclearization, as Pyongyang has done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump after the first summit between an active US president and a North Korean leader on 12 June in Singapore, when Kim pledged to work for the "denuclearization of the Korean peninsula" and Trump ensured North Korea's security.
North Korea has pursued the official end of the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has said that Pyongyang must give up his nuclear weapon.
Washington has also resisted calls for the smoothing of international sanctions to North Korea.
"The United States has insisted on denuclearization in the first place and increased pressure through sanctions in order to achieve its purpose in a coercive manner, even by objecting to a declaration of termination of the war," Ri said.
"The idea that sanctions can make us fall on our knees is a chemera of people who do not know us.
The problem is that the continuation of sanctions deepens our distrust."
Ri made no mention of plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump, announced by the US leader to the United Nations early in the week.
Instead, the minister highlighted three meetings between Kim and Moon Jae, South Korea leader in the last five months, and added: "If South Korea had been interested in denuclearization instead of the United States, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not be in a similar stagnation."
Even so, Ri's speech tone was radically different from last year's speech, when he told the UN General Assembly that it was inevitable to lead North Korea missiles to American soil after Trump's "evil president" on a suicide mission called Kim "a rocket man."
This year at the United Nations, Trump, who last year threatened to "completely destroy" North Korea, praised Kim for his bravery in advancing disarmament, but said that much remained to be done and that further sanctions were needed until North Korea became denuclearized.
On Wednesday, Trump said there was no deadline for this: "We can take two years, three years or five months, no matter."
China and Russia claim that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for its progress.
However, like U.S. Secretary of State, Mike Pompeo, reported to the UN Security Council on Thursday: "The imposition of Security Council sanctions must continue vigorously and without breach until we realize the definitive and fully verified denuclearization."
The Security Council has imposed unanimous sanctions on North Korea since 2006, in an attempt to cut funding for the Pyongyang ballistic and nuclear missile programmes.
Pompeo spoke with Ri outside the UN General Assembly and then commented that he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare a second summit.
Pompeo has already visited North Korea three times this year, but his last trip was not well.
He left Pyongyang in July saying there had been progress, but a few hours later, North Korea denounced that its "requirements were that of a mobster."
At a meeting with Moon this month, North Korea pledged to dismantle a missile site and a nuclear complex if the United States applied the "related measures".
He said that Kim had told him that the "appropriate measures" he was looking for were the security assurances Trump had promised in Singapore and steps towards normalizing relations with Washington.
Harvard students take a course on how to get enough rest
Thanks to a new course this year at Harvard University, all university students sleep more in an attempt to fight the growing Machist culture to study all night drinking caffeine.
One professor found that college number one students in the world often have no idea about the basic care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School, and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital designed the course, is believed to be the first of his class in the United States.
Their motivation to launch the course emerged after giving a talk about how sleep deprivation affects learning.
"At the end of the course, a girl approached and asked me why she just learned about this now, in her last year.
He said that no one had ever talked to him about the importance of the dream, which surprised me," he said to The Telegraph.
The course, first taught this year, explains the basic concepts about how good sleep habits contribute to academic and sports performance, as well as improving overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university's health services, said that the university decided to introduce the course after discovering that students only slept during the week.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one section, there is an image of a bedroom, where students click on cups of coffee, curtains, sports shoes and books that inform them of the effects of caffeine and light, as well as the impact of lack of sleep on sports performance and the importance of establishing a routine to go to sleep.
In another section, participants are informed about how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of infarction, embolism, depression, and cancer.
Then, an icon on the campus with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily routines.
"We know that it's not going to change the behavior of students instantly.
However, we believe that they have the right to know, just as anyone has the right to know the health effects of smoking tobacco," added Professor Czeisler.
He claimed that the culture of pride for "during the night sailing" still exists and added that modern technology and increasing pressure to which students are subjected meant that sleep deprivation was a growing problem.
Sleeping long enough and a good dream should be "the secret weapon" of students to fight stress, fatigue and anxiety; even to avoid gaining weight, since sleep deprivation makes the brain generate a feeling of hunger, so they want to eat all the time.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian who studied chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler to design the course after attending one of his classes the previous year during his first year at Harvard.
He noted that the course had opened his eyes and inspired to extend it to the entire campus.
He hopes that the next step will be to ask all postgraduate students to complete a similar study program before joining the competitive institution.
The recommendation of Professor Czeisler is that students think about setting an alarm to go to bed and another to wake up, and that they are aware of the harmful effects of the "blue light" that emits the screens of electrical appliances and LEDs, which can alter the circadian rhythms, so they would end up having trouble sleeping.
