National Trust spies on the secret life of bats
This new research, which has been carried out in a state of the Scottish Highlands, tries to discover how bats use the landscape in their search for food.
Everything is expected to shed more light on the behaviour of the only flying mammals and help guide the next conservation activities.
The study, carried out by the National Trust for Scotland, will follow the common bats and sopranos, as well as the Daubenton river bats and long-eared browns of the Inverewe gardens in Wester Ross.
Special tape recorders will be placed in strategic locations of the property to track the activities of bats during the season.
The NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile investigations with portable detectors.
The experts will analyze the sounds that are collected in the recordings to discover the frequency of the calls of bats and what species they do.
A report and a map of habitat will then be produced to create a detailed image of the environment and its behavior.
Rob Dewar, nature conservation adviser for NTS, expects the results to reveal which areas of habitat are most important for bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as the creation of meadows and how forests must be maintained for bats and other associated species.
Bats populations in Scotland and the United Kingdom have declined considerably in the last century.
They are under threat from the construction and development that affects their nests and the loss of their habitat.
Wind turbines and electrical wiring can also pose a risk to them, as can insecticide papers and other chemical treatments of building materials or domestic cat attacks.
The bats aren't really blind,
but because of their night hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes to achieve their goal.
They use a sophisticated ecolocation technique that locates ants and obstacles on their flight route.
The NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 major gardens and 76,000 hectares of land throughout the country, takes the topic of bats very seriously.
It has ten experts trained in this field, who are dedicated to carrying out regular surveys, inspections of nests and, sometimes, rescues.
The organization has inaugurated even the first and only reserve dedicated to bats of Scotland in the state of Three in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of the ten species of bats of Scotland.
The property manager, David Thompson, says it is the ideal territory for them.
"Here, in Three, we have a fantastic area for bats," he said.
"We have old buildings, many old trees and all the proper habitat.
However, there are still many unknown things about bats, so the work we do here and in other properties will help us better understand what they need to develop."
It stresses the importance of checking whether there are bats before carrying out maintenance tasks within the properties, as it can involuntaryly destroy a breeding colony and eventually kill 400 females and females, which would mean annihilate a whole local population.
The bats are protected and it is illegal to kill, harass or disturb them, as well as destroy their colonies.
Elisabeth Ferrell, the Scottish Bat Conservation Trust officer, has encouraged the public to cooperate.
He said, "We still have a lot to learn about bats and many other species about which we don't know how their populations evolve."
