Syria is ready to return refugees, says the Minister for Foreign Affairs
Syria states that it is ready for the voluntary return of refugees and calls for assistance in rebuilding a country devastated by a war that has been more than seven years old.
In a speech earlier by the United Nations General Assembly, Foreign Minister Walid al-Moualem said the country's conditions were improving.
"The situation on the ground today is more stable and secure thanks to the progress that has been made in the fight against terrorism," he said.
The government continues to rehabilitate areas destroyed by terrorists to try to restore normality.
All conditions for the voluntary return to the country of the refugees who had to abandon it because of terrorism and the unilateral economic measures that affected their daily lives and livelihoods are already in place.
The UN estimates that since the war began in 2011, more than 5.5 million Syrians have fled the country.
There are another six million people who still live in the country and need humanitarian aid.
Al-Moualem acknowledged that the Syrian regime would appreciate the help to rebuild the devastated country.
But he also stressed that he would not accept conditional aid or assistance from the countries that promoted the insurgency.
