The new report by the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission (Flor Florida Fisheries and Wildlife Commission) shows a general reduction in red tide concentrations in areas of Tampa Bay.
According to the FWC, irregular flowering conditions are being reported in areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties, suggesting a reduction in concentrations.
The flowering of the red tide extends about 130 miles off the coast from Pinellas County north to Lee County south.
You can find irregular plots about 10 miles from Hillsborough County coast, but in fewer places if compared to last week.
Red tide has also been detected in Pasco County.
During the past week, average concentrations have been reported in the County of Pinellas and on its coast, low to high concentrations on the coast of Hillsborough County, high bottom concentrations in the County of Manatee, high bottom concentrations in the County of Sarasota and its coast, mid-bottom concentrations in Charlotte County, high bottom concentrations in the County of Lee and its coast, and low concentrations in the County of Collier.
Respiratory irritation problems in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties continue to be reported.
Respiratory irritation problems have not been reported in the northwestern part of Florida last week.
